DESCRIPTION:
When webapp starts up, it'll send a request to /api/v1/patient-datasets/latest-datasets?instanceId={instanceId}
to get a list of all the currently installed datasets in that instance. This only returns datasets that are active
and associated with that instance id in the patient_dataset_instances table.

For each patient dataset in that list, it'll have an associated entry in the datasets table with the guid
being mapped to the patient_dataset's schema_guid if that dataset is the active revision in that instance.
For each patient dataset without an entry in that table matching the schema_guid, this means that the dataset
is technically installed in that instance, but it is not active.

If there are any issues with webapp starting up and being able to parse a dataset's information, then
webapp skips the dataset, logs the error, and moves on to the next dataset. The result is the datasets
being loaded into the schema cache on startup. Subsequent calls to the schema controller will use the
schema cache.

The exception to datasets that are in scope for this check are deprecated datasets. They will appear
to be installed to the instance still from schema-service, but due to their files no longer existing in the
runtime directory, these datasets will not be loaded into the schema cache when webapp starts up.

In order to detect if the dataset has been loaded correctly, this test will attempt to fetch the dataset's
DatasetInfoPair using the dataset id and the dataset_instance id. If the dataset is not loaded properly by
webapp, then the schema cache won't return anything and we will see an internal error thrown.

If this test fails, check webapp's startup logs. There will most likely be an exception thrown when
attempting to add a dataset to the schema cache loader.
NAME: Verify that webapp is able to load all installed datasets into the schema cache. synpuf_tiny_subset_default_20220720 should be loaded successfully into the schema cache.
SUITE: Verify that webapp is able to load all datasets installed to the instance.

DESCRIPTION:
When webapp starts up, it'll send a request to /api/v1/patient-datasets/latest-datasets?instanceId={instanceId}
to get a list of all the currently installed datasets in that instance. This only returns datasets that are active
and associated with that instance id in the patient_dataset_instances table.

For each patient dataset in that list, it'll have an associated entry in the datasets table with the guid
being mapped to the patient_dataset's schema_guid if that dataset is the active revision in that instance.
For each patient dataset without an entry in that table matching the schema_guid, this means that the dataset
is technically installed in that instance, but it is not active.

If there are any issues with webapp starting up and being able to parse a dataset's information, then
webapp skips the dataset, logs the error, and moves on to the next dataset. The result is the datasets
being loaded into the schema cache on startup. Subsequent calls to the schema controller will use the
schema cache.

The exception to datasets that are in scope for this check are deprecated datasets. They will appear
to be installed to the instance still from schema-service, but due to their files no longer existing in the
runtime directory, these datasets will not be loaded into the schema cache when webapp starts up.

In order to detect if the dataset has been loaded correctly, this test will attempt to fetch the dataset's
DatasetInfoPair using the dataset id and the dataset_instance id. If the dataset is not loaded properly by
webapp, then the schema cache won't return anything and we will see an internal error thrown.

If this test fails, check webapp's startup logs. There will most likely be an exception thrown when
attempting to add a dataset to the schema cache loader.

SUITE: Verify that webapp is able to load all datasets installed to the instance.

DESCRIPTION:
When webapp starts up, it'll send a request to /api/v1/patient-datasets/latest-datasets?instanceId={instanceId}
to get a list of all the currently installed datasets in that instance. This only returns datasets that are active
and associated with that instance id in the patient_dataset_instances table.

For each patient dataset in that list, it'll have an associated entry in the datasets table with the guid
being mapped to the patient_dataset's schema_guid if that dataset is the active revision in that instance.
For each patient dataset without an entry in that table matching the schema_guid, this means that the dataset
is technically installed in that instance, but it is not active.

If there are any issues with webapp starting up and being able to parse a dataset's information, then
webapp skips the dataset, logs the error, and moves on to the next dataset. The result is the datasets
being loaded into the schema cache on startup. Subsequent calls to the schema controller will use the
schema cache.

The exception to datasets that are in scope for this check are deprecated datasets. They will appear
to be installed to the instance still from schema-service, but due to their files no longer existing in the
runtime directory, these datasets will not be loaded into the schema cache when webapp starts up.

In order to detect if the dataset has been loaded correctly, this test will attempt to fetch the dataset's
DatasetInfoPair using the dataset id and the dataset_instance id. If the dataset is not loaded properly by
webapp, then the schema cache won't return anything and we will see an internal error thrown.

If this test fails, check webapp's startup logs. There will most likely be an exception thrown when
attempting to add a dataset to the schema cache loader.

SUITE: Verify that webapp is able to load all datasets installed to the instance.

If there are any issues with webapp starting up and being able to parse a dataset's information, then
webapp skips the dataset, logs the error, and moves on to the next dataset. The result is the datasets
being loaded into the schema cache on startup. Subsequent calls to the schema controller will use the
schema cache.

The exception to datasets that are in scope for this check are deprecated datasets. They will appear
to be installed to the instance still from schema-service, but due to their files no longer existing in the
runtime directory, these datasets will not be loaded into the schema cache when webapp starts up.

In order to detect if the dataset has been loaded correctly, this test will attempt to fetch the dataset's
DatasetInfoPair using the dataset id and the dataset_instance id. If the dataset is not loaded properly by
webapp, then the schema cache won't return anything and we will see an internal error thrown.

If this test fails, check webapp's startup logs. There will most likely be an exception thrown when
attempting to add a dataset to the schema cache loader.

DESCRIPTION:
When webapp starts up, it'll send a request to /api/v1/patient-datasets/latest-datasets?instanceId={instanceId}
to get a list of all the currently installed datasets in that instance. This only returns datasets that are active
and associated with that instance id in the patient_dataset_instances table.

For each patient dataset in that list, it'll have an associated entry in the datasets table with the guid
being mapped to the patient_dataset's schema_guid if that dataset is the active revision in that instance.
For each patient dataset without an entry in that table matching the schema_guid, this means that the dataset
is technically installed in that instance, but it is not active.

If there are any issues with webapp starting up and being able to parse a dataset's information, then
webapp skips the dataset, logs the error, and moves on to the next dataset. The result is the datasets
being loaded into the schema cache on startup. Subsequent calls to the schema controller will use the
schema cache.

The exception to datasets that are in scope for this check are deprecated datasets. They will appear
to be installed to the instance still from schema-service, but due to their files no longer existing in the
runtime directory, these datasets will not be loaded into the schema cache when webapp starts up.

In order to detect if the dataset has been loaded correctly, this test will attempt to fetch the dataset's
DatasetInfoPair using the dataset id and the dataset_instance id. If the dataset is not loaded properly by
webapp, then the schema cache won't return anything and we will see an internal error thrown.

If this test fails, check webapp's startup logs. There will most likely be an exception thrown when
attempting to add a dataset to the schema cache loader.

DESCRIPTION:
When webapp starts up, it'll send a request to /api/v1/patient-datasets/latest-datasets?instanceId={instanceId}
to get a list of all the currently installed datasets in that instance. This only returns datasets that are active
and associated with that instance id in the patient_dataset_instances table.

For each patient dataset in that list, it'll have an associated entry in the datasets table with the guid
being mapped to the patient_dataset's schema_guid if that dataset is the active revision in that instance.
For each patient dataset without an entry in that table matching the schema_guid, this means that the dataset
is technically installed in that instance, but it is not active.

If there are any issues with webapp starting up and being able to parse a dataset's information, then
webapp skips the dataset, logs the error, and moves on to the next dataset. The result is the datasets
being loaded into the schema cache on startup. Subsequent calls to the schema controller will use the
schema cache.

The exception to datasets that are in scope for this check are deprecated datasets. They will appear
to be installed to the instance still from schema-service, but due to their files no longer existing in the
runtime directory, these datasets will not be loaded into the schema cache when webapp starts up.

In order to detect if the dataset has been loaded correctly, this test will attempt to fetch the dataset's
DatasetInfoPair using the dataset id and the dataset_instance id. If the dataset is not loaded properly by
webapp, then the schema cache won't return anything and we will see an internal error thrown.

If this test fails, check webapp's startup logs. There will most likely be an exception thrown when
attempting to add a dataset to the schema cache loader.
NAME: Verify that webapp is able to load all installed datasets into the schema cache. synpuf_adm_adn_2024061102 should be loaded successfully into the schema cache.
SUITE: Verify that webapp is able to load all datasets installed to the instance.

DESCRIPTION:
When webapp starts up, it'll send a request to /api/v1/patient-datasets/latest-datasets?instanceId={instanceId}
to get a list of all the currently installed datasets in that instance. This only returns datasets that are active
and associated with that instance id in the patient_dataset_instances table.

For each patient dataset in that list, it'll have an associated entry in the datasets table with the guid
being mapped to the patient_dataset's schema_guid if that dataset is the active revision in that instance.
For each patient dataset without an entry in that table matching the schema_guid, this means that the dataset
is technically installed in that instance, but it is not active.

If there are any issues with webapp starting up and being able to parse a dataset's information, then
webapp skips the dataset, logs the error, and moves on to the next dataset. The result is the datasets
being loaded into the schema cache on startup. Subsequent calls to the schema controller will use the
schema cache.

The exception to datasets that are in scope for this check are deprecated datasets. They will appear
to be installed to the instance still from schema-service, but due to their files no longer existing in the
runtime directory, these datasets will not be loaded into the schema cache when webapp starts up.

In order to detect if the dataset has been loaded correctly, this test will attempt to fetch the dataset's
DatasetInfoPair using the dataset id and the dataset_instance id. If the dataset is not loaded properly by
webapp, then the schema cache won't return anything and we will see an internal error thrown.

If this test fails, check webapp's startup logs. There will most likely be an exception thrown when
attempting to add a dataset to the schema cache loader.
NAME: Verify that webapp is able to load all installed datasets into the schema cache. synthetic_omop_adn_20250604 should be loaded successfully into the schema cache.
SUITE: Verify that webapp is able to load all datasets installed to the instance.

SUITE: Projects Service - Folders Controller Read-Only Test

DESCRIPTION:
When aep-gateway makes the call to /ui/folders/libraries, there is a series of underlying promises
to projects-service that will grab the root folder with the api call used in this test.
aep-gateway will populate the root folder map with the results of these promises if they are fulfilled.
If projects-service cannot return the root folder in this test, then gateway won't be able to load
them into Substantiate.

DATA_VIEW and DATA_VIEW_DRAFT folder types are excluded because they are not relevant for Substantiate.

If the other test fails, check if this one is working to attempt to isolate the issue.

Note that COHORT_JOB, RESULT_JOB, and CUSTOM_OUTPUT share the same root folder id. All of these
correspond to the job folder.
NAME: Verify that all root library folders are available through projects-service. [10] folderType=CUSTOM_OUTPUT
SUITE: Verify that the folders' tables have been seeded correctly.

DESCRIPTION:
When aep-gateway makes the call to /ui/folders/libraries, there is a series of underlying promises
to projects-service that will grab the root folder with the api call used in this test.
aep-gateway will populate the root folder map with the results of these promises if they are fulfilled.
If projects-service cannot return the root folder in this test, then gateway won't be able to load
them into Substantiate.

DATA_VIEW and DATA_VIEW_DRAFT folder types are excluded because they are not relevant for Substantiate.

If the other test fails, check if this one is working to attempt to isolate the issue.

Note that COHORT_JOB, RESULT_JOB, and CUSTOM_OUTPUT share the same root folder id. All of these
correspond to the job folder.
NAME: Verify that all root library folders are available through projects-service. [4] folderType=COHORT_JOB
SUITE: Verify that the folders' tables have been seeded correctly.

DESCRIPTION:
If this test fails, this means that the measure library has duplicate root folders. This will essentially
brick the entire instance. The SQL selectors to get the root library folder rely on a single result.
That root library folder is how projects-service is able to navigate through the whole website.
Gateway relies on projects-service to be able to make this call. The database should immediately
be investigated if this test fails.
NAME: Verify that each library root folder is singleton. 8 - There should be exactly 1 row in cohort_library_folders that is named "Cohort Library".
SUITE: Verify the database has been set up correctly.

DESCRIPTION:
When aep-gateway makes the call to /ui/folders/libraries, there is a series of underlying promises
to projects-service that will grab the root folder with the api call used in this test.
aep-gateway will populate the root folder map with the results of these promises if they are fulfilled.
If projects-service cannot return the root folder in this test, then gateway won't be able to load
them into Substantiate.

DATA_VIEW and DATA_VIEW_DRAFT folder types are excluded because they are not relevant for Substantiate.

If the other test fails, check if this one is working to attempt to isolate the issue.

Note that COHORT_JOB, RESULT_JOB, and CUSTOM_OUTPUT share the same root folder id. All of these
correspond to the job folder.
NAME: Verify that all root library folders are available through projects-service. [2] folderType=CODE_LIST
SUITE: Verify that the folders' tables have been seeded correctly.

DESCRIPTION:
When aep-gateway makes the call to /ui/folders/libraries, there is a series of underlying promises
to projects-service that will grab the root folder with the api call used in this test.
aep-gateway will populate the root folder map with the results of these promises if they are fulfilled.
If projects-service cannot return the root folder in this test, then gateway won't be able to load
them into Substantiate.

DATA_VIEW and DATA_VIEW_DRAFT folder types are excluded because they are not relevant for Substantiate.

If the other test fails, check if this one is working to attempt to isolate the issue.

Note that COHORT_JOB, RESULT_JOB, and CUSTOM_OUTPUT share the same root folder id. All of these
correspond to the job folder.

DESCRIPTION:
This step creates the following measures to prepare to assert that they will show up as chained measures.
- Any Prescription Drug Event
- Any ICD-9 Diagnosis before 2020
- Any ICD-10 Diagnosis, date range bound by "Any ICD-9 Diagnosis before 2020"

The latter two are created to verify that measure chaining will work with an event set measure that depends on another event set measure's date range.

DESCRIPTION:
When webapp starts up, it'll send a request to /api/v1/patient-datasets/latest-datasets?instanceId={instanceId}
to get a list of all the currently installed datasets in that instance. This only returns datasets that are active
and associated with that instance id in the patient_dataset_instances table.

For each patient dataset in that list, it'll have an associated entry in the datasets table with the guid
being mapped to the patient_dataset's schema_guid if that dataset is the active revision in that instance.
For each patient dataset without an entry in that table matching the schema_guid, this means that the dataset
is technically installed in that instance, but it is not active.

If there are any issues with webapp starting up and being able to parse a dataset's information, then
webapp skips the dataset, logs the error, and moves on to the next dataset. The result is the datasets
being loaded into the schema cache on startup. Subsequent calls to the schema controller will use the
schema cache.

The exception to datasets that are in scope for this check are deprecated datasets. They will appear
to be installed to the instance still from schema-service, but due to their files no longer existing in the
runtime directory, these datasets will not be loaded into the schema cache when webapp starts up.

In order to detect if the dataset has been loaded correctly, this test will attempt to fetch the dataset's
DatasetInfoPair using the dataset id and the dataset_instance id. If the dataset is not loaded properly by
webapp, then the schema cache won't return anything and we will see an internal error thrown.

If this test fails, check webapp's startup logs. There will most likely be an exception thrown when
attempting to add a dataset to the schema cache loader.
NAME: Verify that webapp is able to load all installed datasets into the schema cache. synpuf_subset_default_2024030701 should be loaded successfully into the schema cache.
SUITE: Verify that webapp is able to load all datasets installed to the instance.

DESCRIPTION:
When webapp starts up, it'll send a request to /api/v1/patient-datasets/latest-datasets?instanceId={instanceId}
to get a list of all the currently installed datasets in that instance. This only returns datasets that are active
and associated with that instance id in the patient_dataset_instances table.

For each patient dataset in that list, it'll have an associated entry in the datasets table with the guid
being mapped to the patient_dataset's schema_guid if that dataset is the active revision in that instance.
For each patient dataset without an entry in that table matching the schema_guid, this means that the dataset
is technically installed in that instance, but it is not active.

If there are any issues with webapp starting up and being able to parse a dataset's information, then
webapp skips the dataset, logs the error, and moves on to the next dataset. The result is the datasets
being loaded into the schema cache on startup. Subsequent calls to the schema controller will use the
schema cache.

The exception to datasets that are in scope for this check are deprecated datasets. They will appear
to be installed to the instance still from schema-service, but due to their files no longer existing in the
runtime directory, these datasets will not be loaded into the schema cache when webapp starts up.

In order to detect if the dataset has been loaded correctly, this test will attempt to fetch the dataset's
DatasetInfoPair using the dataset id and the dataset_instance id. If the dataset is not loaded properly by
webapp, then the schema cache won't return anything and we will see an internal error thrown.

If this test fails, check webapp's startup logs. There will most likely be an exception thrown when
attempting to add a dataset to the schema cache loader.
NAME: Verify that webapp is able to load all installed datasets into the schema cache. synpuf_adm_adn_20240611 should be loaded successfully into the schema cache.
SUITE: Verify that webapp is able to load all datasets installed to the instance.

DESCRIPTION:
If this test fails, this means that the measure library has duplicate root folders. This will essentially
brick the entire instance. The SQL selectors to get the root library folder rely on a single result.
That root library folder is how projects-service is able to navigate through the whole website.
Gateway relies on projects-service to be able to make this call. The database should immediately
be investigated if this test fails.
NAME: Verify that each library root folder is singleton. 1 - There should be exactly 1 row in job_library_folders that is global.
SUITE: Verify the database has been set up correctly.

DESCRIPTION:
When aep-gateway makes the call to /ui/folders/libraries, there is a series of underlying promises
to projects-service that will grab the root folder with the api call used in this test.
aep-gateway will populate the root folder map with the results of these promises if they are fulfilled.
If projects-service cannot return the root folder in this test, then gateway won't be able to load
them into Substantiate.

DATA_VIEW and DATA_VIEW_DRAFT folder types are excluded because they are not relevant for Substantiate.

If the other test fails, check if this one is working to attempt to isolate the issue.

Note that COHORT_JOB, RESULT_JOB, and CUSTOM_OUTPUT share the same root folder id. All of these
correspond to the job folder.

SUITE: Verify that the folders' tables have been seeded correctly.

DESCRIPTION:
When webapp starts up, it'll send a request to /api/v1/patient-datasets/latest-datasets?instanceId={instanceId}
to get a list of all the currently installed datasets in that instance. This only returns datasets that are active
and associated with that instance id in the patient_dataset_instances table.

For each patient dataset in that list, it'll have an associated entry in the datasets table with the guid
being mapped to the patient_dataset's schema_guid if that dataset is the active revision in that instance.
For each patient dataset without an entry in that table matching the schema_guid, this means that the dataset
is technically installed in that instance, but it is not active.

If there are any issues with webapp starting up and being able to parse a dataset's information, then
webapp skips the dataset, logs the error, and moves on to the next dataset. The result is the datasets
being loaded into the schema cache on startup. Subsequent calls to the schema controller will use the
schema cache.

The exception to datasets that are in scope for this check are deprecated datasets. They will appear
to be installed to the instance still from schema-service, but due to their files no longer existing in the
runtime directory, these datasets will not be loaded into the schema cache when webapp starts up.

In order to detect if the dataset has been loaded correctly, this test will attempt to fetch the dataset's
DatasetInfoPair using the dataset id and the dataset_instance id. If the dataset is not loaded properly by
webapp, then the schema cache won't return anything and we will see an internal error thrown.

If this test fails, check webapp's startup logs. There will most likely be an exception thrown when
attempting to add a dataset to the schema cache loader.
NAME: Verify that webapp is able to load all installed datasets into the schema cache. marketscan_adm_default_20240523 should be loaded successfully into the schema cache.
SUITE: Verify that webapp is able to load all datasets installed to the instance.

DESCRIPTION:
When webapp starts up, it'll send a request to /api/v1/patient-datasets/latest-datasets?instanceId={instanceId}
to get a list of all the currently installed datasets in that instance. This only returns datasets that are active
and associated with that instance id in the patient_dataset_instances table.

For each patient dataset in that list, it'll have an associated entry in the datasets table with the guid
being mapped to the patient_dataset's schema_guid if that dataset is the active revision in that instance.
For each patient dataset without an entry in that table matching the schema_guid, this means that the dataset
is technically installed in that instance, but it is not active.

If there are any issues with webapp starting up and being able to parse a dataset's information, then
webapp skips the dataset, logs the error, and moves on to the next dataset. The result is the datasets
being loaded into the schema cache on startup. Subsequent calls to the schema controller will use the
schema cache.

The exception to datasets that are in scope for this check are deprecated datasets. They will appear
to be installed to the instance still from schema-service, but due to their files no longer existing in the
runtime directory, these datasets will not be loaded into the schema cache when webapp starts up.

In order to detect if the dataset has been loaded correctly, this test will attempt to fetch the dataset's
DatasetInfoPair using the dataset id and the dataset_instance id. If the dataset is not loaded properly by
webapp, then the schema cache won't return anything and we will see an internal error thrown.

If this test fails, check webapp's startup logs. There will most likely be an exception thrown when
attempting to add a dataset to the schema cache loader.
NAME: Verify that webapp is able to load all installed datasets into the schema cache. marketscan_tiny_adm_default_20241206 should be loaded successfully into the schema cache.
SUITE: Verify that webapp is able to load all datasets installed to the instance.
